MK1 Patch Execution Protocol
Purpose

This protocol defines how patches are proposed, applied, tested, and continued during MK1 development.

It is designed for fast iteration while preserving deterministic, auditable development practices consistent with MK1 architecture.

Core Working Rule

Work proceeds in small sequential patches.

For each patch cycle, the assistant must provide in the same message:

the patch code
the exact file(s) the patch applies to
test code and/or test instructions
the expected pass condition
the next file needed for the following patch
any specific output required from testing

This allows patching and testing to occur while the next step is already prepared.

Patch Boundaries

Each patch must explicitly state:

file(s) allowed to change
purpose of the patch
invariants touched, if any
whether unseen surrounding code is required

The assistant must not assume permission to modify files beyond those named in the patch.

No Guessing Rule

If the assistant requires code context not already provided, it must ask for the current file and must not guess missing implementation details.

If behavior, ownership, or routing location is unclear, the assistant must ask before patching.

Spelling and typing mistakes from the user are the only place where best-effort interpretation is allowed.

Test Return Rule

Default rule:

if no special return is requested, sending the next file is treated as confirmation that the prior patch passed

If specific validation is required, the assistant must say exactly what to return, such as:

terminal output
traceback
generated artifact path
database query result
diff snippet
Failure Rule

If a patch fails, normal forward patching stops.

Troubleshooting begins immediately using the failure output.

Failure returns should include:

exact command run
full terminal output or traceback
confirmation that the file was edited exactly as provided
any extra manual changes made locally

Once resolved, the normal patch → test → next patch cycle resumes.

Patch Size Rule

Patches should be the smallest safe implementation step.

Avoid redesign, hidden routing changes, schema drift, or unrelated cleanup unless required to fix incorrect behavior.

This preserves deterministic, auditable development and aligns with MK1 change policy.

main.py Rule

main.py is treated as a runner and display surface only.

Patches must not move routing logic, pipeline ownership, or control-plane behavior into main.py.

Routing Rule

Any patch affecting routing must respect the routing single source of truth.

Routing logic belongs only in the capability registry / deterministic routing layer, not in ad hoc expert logic or patch-local shortcuts.

Side-Effect Rule

Only explicitly side-effecting experts may write persistent state.

Patches must not introduce hidden writes, implicit DB mutations, or uncontrolled file output.

Recommended Patch Message Format

Each patch message should use this structure:

Patch Goal
What this patch changes.

Files
Exact file(s) to modify.

Invariants Touched
List or none.

Patch
Code block(s), properly indented and ready to paste.

Test
Exact command(s) to run.

Expected Result
What passing looks like.

Return To Me
Exact output needed, or none (sending next file implies pass).

Next File Needed
Name of the file required for the next patch.